"Yes, sir. You should be on your way by now, they were still in the mess hall to pick up their rations."         At exactly 0500, the Exodus Company assembled at the vehicle park. Shaw climbed onto a crate and began to speak.
"We are being relocated to the forward operating base I-131, fifty miles outside of Ianlos. Our task is to support the ongoing siege and the subsequent attack on Ianlos in order to drive out the rebels. There we will establish a base camp at the foot of the mountains," explained Shaw. "Move out to your squads and mount up."
The company broke up into their respective squads, and the soldiers were distributed by the corporals onto the tanks. Cohren climbed onto one of the tanks further forward in the convoy, where he met Nemic, Craith and two new recruits. Cohren remembered the arrival of the two a few days ago, but knew little about them. He sat on the side and let his legs swing while he adjusted his backpack and the radio, which was connected to his headset and throat microphone.
"Hey Cohren, is Snowball still with Harris?" asked Nemic after they had settled in.
"Do you mean the rooster he stole?" Cohren remembered the morning when they let the animal go on a farm. "Yes, I think so."
Cohren looked over to one of the other tanks and spotted Harris with his squad. From the corner of his eye, he could make out the movement of a small rooster, which was scanning the surroundings by constantly turning its head.
„Yes, he's still with him," answered Cohren as the tank's hatch opened and the commander came into view.
„All tanks advance," said the commander slowly and calmly into his headset. The engines of the column of tanks and Strykers roared as they moved. The Kronos tank, which Cohren was riding in, shook as the brake was released and they joined the formation. The tanks moved in a wedge formation across the Itania plain. Due to the winter storms, the swamp areas had frozen and the forests were snow-covered, nevertheless, the mud was omnipresent.
After about an hour, one of the recruits, whom Cohren knew was named Orson, began to speak. „Lieutenant, you've been here since the start of the war, right?“
„Yes, Operation Firestorm," answered Cohren. „We thought the matter would be settled in a few weeks, but we underestimated them.“
"Underestimated is strongly understated," Nemic interjected. "We were not prepared for their arsenal of weapons and the sheer number of soldiers. They destroyed the UFS Revenant in the first two weeks and only last month the Erebus. We should have even seen them on our way."
"I stand firmly by the Federation's side," said Orson stubbornly. "I will not let these terrorists scare me."
"That's what you say now. But I've seen that most of the eighteen-year-old recruits like you quickly take cover as soon as they hear a shot," explained Craith.
"We'll see about that," said Cohren laughing. Orson ended the conversation.
"Exodus XO, Exodus CO," crackled Cohren's radio. "We are receiving heat signatures, good 300 meters away, 20 degrees to the right."
Cohren climbed up onto the tank and put on his special glasses. When he switched them to "thermal imaging," he could recognize the signatures in the distance.
"Yes, I see them," answered Cohren over his laryngeal microphone.
"Are they hostile?" asked the other recruit, Natayla.
"I can't tell," answered Cohren. He reached for his microphone and said: "Exodus Company, fire only when under fire. Lure them out."
As they approached, the point-like thermal signatures took shape. As they came even closer, one of them hurried off to get something. Immediately, she returned to the small hill where the others were. The figures lay down on the ground, they took up firing positions.
"We have enemy contact," Shaw shouted over the radio as orange tracer rounds were fired from the hillside. While the tanks came under fire, the assault troops jumped down and took cover. A rocket zoomed past and hit behind the formation, exploded, and scattered debris and rubble onto one of the tanks. Another struck sideways into a Stryker, an APS-Cerberus, and exploded. The crew quickly climbed out and took cover as the ammunition went up in flames.
"Iron 1-2 and 1-3, 25 degrees right, 300 meters. Fire," the tank platoon commander shouted over the radio. Iron 1-2 and 1-3 opened fire, grenades flew toward the hillside and exploded, hurling mud and rock into the air.
"Send in the Sentis," Knoxx called, watching the hillside through a pair of binoculars. The rear hatch of a Cerberus opened and an unarmed soldier came out, wearing a special headset. He gave orders into a square microphone, and two Sentis, officially called Sentinels, stormed out. Swinging their slender, metallic arms and legs forward, they started sprinting. They carried their weapons on their backs.
"Kill or capture?" Craith asked as they watched.
"Looks like capture," Cohren guessed as the two Sentinels disappeared into the ash and smoke cloud. Screams and gunfire echoed from the hillside, but quickly fell silent. Shortly afterwards, the two Sentinels returned and dragged someone behind them, whose boots left tracks in the ground. After returning to the cover of the platoon, they threw the figure to the ground. She groaned in pain as she landed hard in the mud and snow.
Shaw approached the figure who was just trying to get up. Then he turned to one of the Sentinels. "How many?"
"Three dead, Sir," replied the Sentinel. "The rest ran away on foot."
Shaw nodded and turned to Cohren and Craith, who were standing nearby. "Get this guy out of my sight!"
